{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":30151,"record_hash":"sha256:2e529966957d4d99c1797583dfcf5f1a877d486e24166772aafcd94f6b35ef4f","timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:34:18.490Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: agent-session-capture/agentlog-sync-lifecycle.md\n+# Agentlog Sync Lifecycle\n+\n+This note sketches a future hidden command:\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog sync [--remote <name>]\n+```\n+\n+The command should exchange only GitButler agentlog metadata. Capture remains a\n+local operation; sync is the explicit lifecycle step that sends captured\n+metadata to a remote and receives metadata captured elsewhere.\n+\n+## Goals\n+\n+- Send and receive agentlog metadata through GitMeta refs.\n+- Keep the command scoped to agentlog keys, not every shareable GitMeta key.\n+- Materialize received metadata back into local SQLite so readers can query it\n+  normally.\n+- Reuse GitMeta library APIs for serialization, fetch, push, conflict handling,\n+  and materialization.\n+- Keep hook/capture commands local-only and fast.\n+\n+## Non-Goals\n+\n+- Do not make capture or hooks push metadata.\n+- Do not sync unrelated GitMeta namespaces.\n+- Do not infer branch or pull request ownership.\n+- Do not implement custom Git transport in `but-agentlog`.\n+- Do not silently install persistent project filter rules just to make this\n+  command work.\n+\n+## Agentlog Key Scope\n+\n+Agentlog sync should include:\n+\n+```text\n+gitbutler:agent-sessions\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n+```\n+\n+The first key may appear on the `project` target as the session index and on\n+future branch/change/commit targets as relationship references. The durable\n+session data stays on the `project` target.\n+\n+No `meta:local:*` values should be synced. If future implementation adds\n+private or machine-local agentlog state, keep it outside this command's\n+published key scope.\n+\n+## Command Shape\n+\n+Initial POC command:\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog sync [--remote <name>]\n+```\n+\n+Behavior:\n+\n+1. Resolve the GitMeta remote.\n+2. Fetch the agentlog metadata ref from that remote.\n+3. Materialize fetched agentlog metadata into local GitMeta SQLite.\n+4. Serialize local agentlog keys into the agentlog metadata ref.\n+5. Push that ref to the remote.\n+6. On non-fast-forward push rejection, fetch, materialize, re-serialize, and\n+   retry a small bounded number of times.\n+\n+The command does not need an agent argument. It operates on stored GitMeta\n+agentlog data, not on a live provider transcript.\n+\n+Human output can stay terse:\n+\n+```text\n+Synced agentlog metadata with origin\n+```\n+\n+JSON output can mirror that with a simple object. More detailed counters are\n+useful later, but not required for the first lifecycle POC.\n+\n+## GitMeta API Implication\n+\n+The current high-level GitMeta APIs are close but not quite the right shape for\n+agentlog-only sync:\n+\n+- `Session::serialize()` serializes all shareable metadata according to global\n+  filter rules.\n+- `Session::pull()` fetches and materializes configured metadata refs.\n+- `Session::push_once()` pushes the main serialized metadata ref.\n+\n+Using those directly would make `but agentlog sync` exchange unrelated metadata\n+too. That breaks the command's scope.\n+\n+Prefer a small GitMeta API extension over reimplementing transport in\n+`but-agentlog`. The API should let a caller exchange a named destination or an\n+explicit key scope. Conceptually:\n+\n+```text\n+serialize only keys matching:\n+  gitbutler:agent-sessions\n+  gitbutler:agent-session:**\n+\n+write local ref:\n+  refs/meta/local/agentlog\n+\n+fetch/push remote ref configured for:\n+  agentlog\n+\n+materialize only that fetched agentlog ref\n+```\n+\n+Exact function names can be decided in `git-meta`, but the important API\n+property is that key scope is command-scoped, not achieved by mutating the\n+user's persistent `meta:filter` or `meta:local:filter` configuration.\n+\n+## Suggested Exchange Shape\n+\n+Use a dedicated GitMeta destination for agentlog metadata:\n+\n+```text\n+local:  refs/meta/local/agentlog\n+remote: configured agentlog metadata ref\n+```\n+\n+This is cleaner than publishing agentlog into the default metadata ref because:\n+\n+- the command can honestly claim to sync only agentlog data\n+- future GitButler metadata can have different privacy and publishing policy\n+- large transcript data can be reasoned about separately from smaller metadata\n+- a backend or teammate can fetch/materialize only the agentlog destination\n+\n+The exact remote ref name should follow GitMeta destination configuration rather\n+than being hardcoded in `but-agentlog`.\n+\n+## Ordering And Dedupe\n+\n+Remote materialization can merge metadata from multiple machines. Readers should\n+not depend on stored GitMeta list order. After sync, consumers should:\n+\n+- dedupe transcript records by `record_hash`\n+- sort by `source_key` and `record_index` within one source\n+- use `timestamp`, `source_key`, `record_index`, and `record_hash` as stable\n+  ordering inputs across multiple sources\n+\n+This matches the data model documented in\n+[GitMeta Data Model](gitmeta-data-model.md).\n+\n+## Privacy Posture\n+\n+`agentlog sync` should be explicit in the first implementation. Captured\n+transcripts are redacted, but they can still reveal sensitive project context,\n+prompting strategy, file names inside tool commands, and architectural details.\n+\n+Future GitButler UX can decide whether agentlog sync is:\n+\n+- manual only\n+- part of a GitButler \"sync workspace\" action\n+- part of branch/PR publish\n+- best-effort background sync for opted-in projects\n+\n+That policy should live above `but-agentlog`; the crate should provide a small\n+sync primitive and clear result reporting.\n+\n+## Failure Handling\n+\n+For the explicit command:\n+\n+- missing GitMeta remote should fail clearly\n+- fetch/materialize failure should fail the command\n+- push non-fast-forward should retry after fetch/materialize/re-serialize\n+- repeated push failure should fail clearly\n+- no remote data and no local changes should succeed with an up-to-date message\n+\n+For future integration with normal GitButler push/fetch flows, the product needs\n+to decide whether metadata sync failure blocks code sync or is reported as a\n+recoverable warning.\n+\n+## Open Questions\n+\n+- Should `but agentlog sync` default to the first configured GitMeta remote, or\n+  should GitButler derive a metadata remote from `origin` when none exists?\n+- What remote destination name should GitMeta expose for agentlog: `agentlog`,\n+  `gitbutler-agentlog`, or a GitButler-managed configured name?\n+- Should the first implementation support `--push-only` or `--pull-only`, or\n+  keep one full sync command until there is a concrete need?\n+- Should GitButler web/review infrastructure materialize the same agentlog\n+  destination directly, or should a backend ingest it into another store after\n+  Git transport?\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:34:18.490Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}